editorial:
**Approach**: Single stack of `[prevString, k]` pairs. Walk through string maintaining `cur` string aur `k` counter.

- Digit dikhe toh `k = k*10 + digit` (multi-digit support).
- `[` aaye toh `(cur, k)` push, fir `cur=''`, `k=0`.
- `]` aaye toh pop `(prev, pk)`, `cur = prev + cur.repeat(pk)`.
- Letter aaye toh `cur += letter`.

```js
function decodeString(s){
  const st=[]; let cur='', k=0;
  for(const c of s){
    if(c>='0'&&c<='9') k=k*10+Number(c);
    else if(c==='['){ st.push([cur,k]); cur=''; k=0; }
    else if(c===']'){ const [p,pk]=st.pop(); cur=p+cur.repeat(pk); }
    else cur+=c;
  }
  return cur;
}
```

Nesting handle ho jaata hai naturally kyunki innermost `]` pehle process hota hai.

**Complexity**: O(N) jahaan N output length hai (kyunki repeat costs).

