editorial:
**Brute force**: O(n*k).

**Monotonic deque** (O(n)): indices ki deque maintain kar jisme corresponding values strictly decreasing hain. Front hamesha current window ka max index.

Har i pe:
1. Front se window-out indices hatao (`dq[0] <= i-k`).
2. Back se `a[i]` se chhoti values wale indices pop karo (smaller dimag se nahi rakhne — kyunki bigger element aa gaya).
3. `i` push.
4. `i >= k-1` ho toh result mein `a[dq[0]]` daal.

```js
function maxSlidingWindow(a,k){
  const dq=[], r=[];
  for(let i=0;i<a.length;i++){
    while(dq.length && dq[0]<=i-k) dq.shift();
    while(dq.length && a[dq[dq.length-1]]<a[i]) dq.pop();
    dq.push(i);
    if(i>=k-1) r.push(a[dq[0]]);
  }
  return r;
}
```

`shift()` JS mein O(n) hai technically, prod code mein index-based circular deque better. Yahaan small inputs ke liye chal jaayega.

**Complexity**: O(n) amortized, O(k) space.

